{"parse":{"title":"John Yeon","pageid":12918511,"revid":851345868,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">This article is about the architect, designer and conservationist John Yeon. For the timber businessman and father of the architect, see <a href=\"/wiki/John_B._Yeon\" title=\"John B. Yeon\">John B. Yeon</a>.</div>\n<table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">John Yeon</span></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:John_Yeon.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"John Yeon.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bb/John_Yeon.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"400\" data-file-width=\"200\" data-file-height=\"400\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n<span style=\"display:none\">(<span class=\"bday\">1910-10-29</span>)</span>October 29, 1910<br /><span class=\"birthplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Portland,_Oregon\" title=\"Portland, Oregon\">Portland, Oregon</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">U.S.</a></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>\nMarch 13, 1994<span style=\"display:none\">(1994-03-13)</span> (aged&#160;83)<br /><span class=\"deathplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Portland,_Oregon\" title=\"Portland, Oregon\">Portland, Oregon</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">U.S.</a></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Nationality</th><td class=\"category\">\nAmerican</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Occupation</th><td class=\"role\">\nArchitect</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Awards</th><td>\nBrunner Prize, Aubrey Watzek Award, Distinguished Service Award (University of Oregon)</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>John Yeon</b> (October 29, 1910 &#8211; March 13, 1994) was an <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American</a> architect in <a href=\"/wiki/Portland,_Oregon\" title=\"Portland, Oregon\">Portland, Oregon</a>, in the mid-twentieth century.  He is regarded as one of the early practitioners of the <a href=\"/wiki/Northwest_Regional_style\" title=\"Northwest Regional style\">Northwest Regional style</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Modern_architecture\" title=\"Modern architecture\">Modernism</a>. Largely self-taught, Yeon\u2019s wide ranging activities encompassed planning, conservation, historic preservation, art collecting, and urban activism. He was a connoisseur of objets d\u2019art as well as landscapes, and one of Oregon\u2019s most gifted architectural designers, even while his output was limited.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The family name is pronounced \"yawn\", not \"yee-on\".\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Early_life\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Early life</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Architecture\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Architecture</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#The_John_Yeon_Center\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">The John Yeon Center</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Retrospective\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Retrospective</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Further_reading\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Further reading</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Early_life\">Early life</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=John_Yeon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Early life\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>John Yeon was born in Portland on October 29, 1910, the son of <a href=\"/wiki/John_B._Yeon\" title=\"John B. Yeon\">John B. Yeon</a> and Elizabeth Mock Yeon.<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The elder was a lumber baron and construction manager who oversaw the building of the <a href=\"/wiki/Historic_Columbia_River_Highway\" title=\"Historic Columbia River Highway\">Columbia River Highway</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and developer of Portland's Yeon Building. The younger Yeon was raised in Portland and attended Allen Preparatory School in that city before leaving for <a href=\"/wiki/California\" title=\"California\">California</a> to attend <a href=\"/wiki/Stanford_University\" title=\"Stanford University\">Stanford University</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> An autodidact and polymath, Yeon attended the college for just a single semester before leaving and never became a licensed architect.<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Architecture\">Architecture</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=John_Yeon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Architecture\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:242px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_(Portland,_Oregon).jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_%28Portland%2C_Oregon%29.jpg/240px-Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_%28Portland%2C_Oregon%29.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"160\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_%28Portland%2C_Oregon%29.jpg/360px-Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_%28Portland%2C_Oregon%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_%28Portland%2C_Oregon%29.jpg/480px-Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_%28Portland%2C_Oregon%29.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"4608\" data-file-height=\"3072\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Aubrey_R_Watzek_House_2_(Portland,_Oregon).jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Watzek House</div></div></div>\n<p>His first built work\u2013the 1937 Watzek House\u2013was included in a 1939 publication and accompanying exhibition by the Museum of Modern Art. His most notable works include the aforementioned <a href=\"/wiki/Aubrey_R._Watzek_House\" title=\"Aubrey R. Watzek House\">Aubrey R. Watzek House</a> (1937)<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and the Portland <a href=\"/wiki/Visitors_Information_Center_(Portland,_Oregon)\" title=\"Visitors Information Center (Portland, Oregon)\">Visitors Information Center</a> (1949), both of which were featured in exhibits at the <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Modern_Art\" title=\"Museum of Modern Art\">Museum of Modern Art</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/New_York_City\" title=\"New York City\">New York City</a>. The Watzek house is listed on the <a href=\"/wiki/National_Register_of_Historic_Places\" title=\"National Register of Historic Places\">National Register of Historic Places</a>. The <a href=\"/wiki/John_Yeon_Speculative_House\" title=\"John Yeon Speculative House\">John Yeon Speculative House</a> (1939), one of the best-preserved of his nine \"speculative house\" series, was added to the National Register of Historic Places in August 2007.  Yeon also designed museum exhibitions, including those for the <a href=\"/wiki/Portland_Art_Museum\" title=\"Portland Art Museum\">Portland Art Museum</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art\" title=\"Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art\">Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Asian_Art_Museum_of_San_Francisco\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Asian Art Museum of San Francisco\">Asian Art Museum</a> in San Francisco, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Palace_of_the_Legion_of_Honor\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Palace of the Legion of Honor\">Palace of the Legion of Honor</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1956, Yeon was awarded the Brunner Prize for architecture by the National Institute of Arts.<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Oregon\" title=\"University of Oregon\">University of Oregon</a> awarded him a Distinguished Service Award in 1977, and <a href=\"/wiki/Lewis_%26_Clark_College\" title=\"Lewis &amp; Clark College\">Lewis &amp; Clark College</a> gave him its annual Aubrey Watzek Award in 1980.<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>John Yeon died in Portland on Sunday, March 13, 1994, of congestive heart failure.<sup id=\"cite_ref-obit_2-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-obit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"The_John_Yeon_Center\">The John Yeon Center</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=John_Yeon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: The John Yeon Center\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>A gift on behalf of the estate of John Yeon was made to the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Oregon\" title=\"University of Oregon\">University of Oregon</a> School of Architecture and Allied Arts, which established the John Yeon Center for Architecture and the John Yeon Preserve for Landscape Studies.  The John Yeon Center sponsors a John Yeon Lecture Series, Faculty Grant Program, Yeon Graduate Teaching Fellowship, and Advisory Board for architecture and historic preservation.  The Yeon Center includes the Aubrey Watzek House, the Cottrell House (1950) and Yeon's personal landscape architecture property, The Shire, in Skamania County, Washington which looks across the Columbia River, facing Multnomah Falls. Part of the University of Oregon\u2019s School of Architecture and Allied Arts, the Center manages and programs three properties designed by Yeon: the Watzek House (1937), a National Historic Landmark; the Cottrell House (1952), and the Shire, a 75-acre park in the Columbia River Gorge. The current director of the John Yeon Center is Randy Gragg.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Retrospective\">Retrospective</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=John_Yeon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Retrospective\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><i>Quest for Beauty: The Architecture, Landscapes, and Collections of John Yeon</i>, a major retrospective of Yeon's work, opened at the Portland Art Museum on May 13 and ran through September 3, 2017.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The exhibit was designed by Lever Architecture of Portland, OR. Two new monographs, <i>John Yeon: Architecture</i> and <i>John Yeon: Landscape,</i> were published by Andrea Monfried Editions in conjunction with the new exhibition. Illustrated with drawings, plans and photographs, the books include essays by the director of the John Yeon Center, Randy Gragg, and other contributors, who explore his approach and contextualize his influence.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=John_Yeon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Bosker, Gideon, and Lena Lencek.  <i>Frozen Music: A History of Portland Architecture</i>.  Portland: <a href=\"/wiki/Oregon_Historical_Society\" title=\"Oregon Historical Society\">Oregon Historical Society</a>, 1985.</li>\n<li>Placzek, Adolf K., ed.  \"Yeon, John.\"  <i>Macmillan Encyclopedia of Architects</i>.  New York: Free Press, 1982.</li>\n<li>Randy Gragg (Editor), Brian Ferriso (Foreword), Barry Bergdoll (Contributor), J. M. Cava (Contributor), Marc Treib (Contributor). <i><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.accpublishinggroup.com/us/store/pv/9780991026371/john-yeon-architecture/randy-gragg-editor-foreword-by-brian-ferriso-essayists-barry-bergdoll-j-m-cava-and-marc-treib/\">John Yeon Architecture: Building in the Pacific Northwest.</a></i> Andrea Monfried Editions, New York, June 2017</li>\n<li>Randy Gragg (Editor), Susan Seubert (Photographer), Bowen Blair (Contributor), Kenneth Helphand (Contributor) <i><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.accpublishinggroup.com/us/store/pv/9780991026388/john-yeon-landscape/randy-gragg-editor-susan-seubert-photographer-bowen-blair-essay-kenneth-helphand-essay/\">John Yeon Landscape: Design, Conservation, Activism.</a></i> Andrea Monfried Editions, New York, June 2017</li>\n<li>Marc Treib, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.oroeditions.com/book/john-yeon\"><i>John Yeon Modern Architecture and Conservation in the Pacific Northwest</i></a> December 2016, Oro Editions</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=John_Yeon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://oregonencyclopedia.org/articles/john_yeon/#.WTYMAhPyvjA\">\"John Yeon (1910-1994)\"</a>. <i>oregonencyclopedia.org</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2017-06-06</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=oregonencyclopedia.org&amp;rft.atitle=John+Yeon+%281910-1994%29&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Foregonencyclopedia.org%2Farticles%2Fjohn_yeon%2F%23.WTYMAhPyvjA&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJohn+Yeon\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-obit-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-6\"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-obit_2-7\"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Hortsch, Dan. Nationally-known architectural designer dies. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Oregonian\" title=\"The Oregonian\">The Oregonian</a></i>, March 15, 1994.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Leland M. Roth, <i>American Architecture: A History</i> (Boulder: Westview, 2001), 362-363.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://portlandartmuseum.org/exhibitions/quest-for-beauty/\">\"Quest for Beauty: The Architecture, Landscapes, and Collections of John Yeon\"</a>. <i>portlandartmuseum.org</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2017-08-15</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=portlandartmuseum.org&amp;rft.atitle=Quest+for+Beauty%3A+The+Architecture%2C+Landscapes%2C+and+Collections+of+John+Yeon&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fportlandartmuseum.org%2Fexhibitions%2Fquest-for-beauty%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJohn+Yeon\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png\" width=\"50\" height=\"39\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.s